From the SEM images (Fig. 2
                        ), we can find that the sample has a very special morphology. The sample shows that a three-dimensional nanoflower-like structure (Fig. 2c) formed by a plurality of nanosheets is grown on the one-dimensional nanorod (Fig. 2b). The average diameter of the nanoflower that we calculated is 0.2553 μm. Fig. 3
                        a and 3c show the TEM images of the nanosheet and the nanorod, respectively (Fig. 3b and 3d are the HRTEM images, corresponding to the nanosheet and nanorod, respectively). From the image we can confirm that graphene quantum dots have been successfully doped in this composite structure.

Period to this, we need to know that ZnO is a hexagonal crystal structure in which oxygen atoms and zinc atoms are stacked. In the early stage of growth, because of the top polar zinc plane (0001) and the substrate polar oxygen plane (
000
1 ‾
) of the ZnO that relative to the symmetric non-polar plane {
10
1 ‾
0
}, they have a lower surface energy. Because the growth of the crystal always develops along the lowest direction of the total surface energy of the system, it will grow along the (0001) direction without the surfactant environment, and finally form the stalks (Fig. 5 a: one-dimensional nanorod). It's well known that the growth of ZnO in aqueous solution is affected by many external factors, such as pH values, solution concentration, solution temperature and atomic arrangement of the growth surface. As the reaction proceeds further, the pH value of the reaction solution is continuously rising. The non-growth ions combine with the polar surface (Fig. 5b), causing the crystal to start along the {
10
1 ‾
0
} direction. Finally, a nanoflower composed of two-dimensional nanosheets is formed. According to the report of Takada Toshio and co-authors, we can know that there is a tight relationship between zinc ion concentration and pH value [28]. We believe that the pH value between 9 and 11 is the morphology transition point (MTP) (Fig. 5c). We know that there are Zn2+, Zn(OH)-, Zn(OH)2, Zn(OH)3 -, Zn(OH)4 2− ions in the solution. When pH value below 9, the growth ion Zn(OH)3 - and Zn(OH)4 2− grows in combination with the polar plane. However, when the pH value is at the MTP, it indicates that Zn(OH)2 is mainly present in the solution, and the crystal growth become slower. At this time, the non-growth ion and the polar plane combine to strengthen. When the pH value is over 11, a large amount of non-growth ions competes with the growth ions to further strengthen, which greatly hinders the combination of the growth ions and the polar plane. However, at this time, the crystal begins to grow along the {
10
1 ‾
0
} direction, forming a two-dimensional nanosheet structure, and finally the combination becomes corolla structure (Fig. 5d).

In the simulation results (Fig. 6
                           ), we find that under this operating condition, the electric field distribution in the thin film decreases from the top to the bottom. Therefore, we believe that when ultraviolet light is irradiated onto the sample, the photo-generated electron-hole pairs generated on the nanoflowers and the nanorods move along the nanorods toward lower potential direction. Then, it is separated by a transverse electric field at the intersection of the nanorods and the seed layer to generate a signal finally. This process is schematically shown in Fig. 7
                           .
